In one sense HG is perfectly right about selective memory, and the fact that the movie industry has churned out utter crap all through history.<br>
<br>
BUT: There has been a constant development towards greater and greater monopolization of the industry (along with most other cultural forms, such as music and comics). And the media giants mostly care about one thing: the bottom line. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
This leads to a very strong focus on &quot;saleability&quot;, which again leads filmmakers to look for concepts that are easy to sell, rather than complex, &quot;artistic&quot; projects. This in turn leads script writers and directors to adapt their products so that they will more easily appeal to investors, to attract enough moolah to get their film off the drawing board.<br>
<br>
Which in turn leads to utterly predictable and unexciting projects, often extremely formulaic and very politically correct without actually saying anything relevant. This is why independent films and smaller projects are very often far more interesting than the big blockbusters.<br>
<br>
In addition you get a rather inbred industry that endlessly assimilates new talents, turning them into new versions of the same old same old. I've seen this several times: A promising young filmmaker gets sucked in by Hollywood and ends up creating crap. It's all in the political economy of the cultural industry.<br>
<br>
And in a dialectical process, the public, accustomed to constantly being underestimated, begins to prefer massproduced crap over real art. There's just so many commercial campaigns people can withstand before succumbing. After all, many of us go to see films like MIB2, even though we KNOW it's gonna suck big time.<br>
<br>
I *think*, although I'm not sure, that this process has come further in the USA than in Europe, possibly because many European countries has a less commercially-inclined cultural milieu. (Although we have lots of crap here too...) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#111111><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/blucifer.showUserPublicProfile?gid=batmite@lucifer>BatMite</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#FFFF99>(10/14/03 9:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fluciferfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.comicboards.com/teentitans/moderator/batmite.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Dumb movies</span><hr size=1> I don't think it is selective memory. I remember plenty of bad old movies. It is just that, I believe that bad movies are getting dumber today. The other day I rented 'KRULL' because I sorta remembered that I kinda liked it as a kid ... yes ... I know ... 'KRULL' .... I was FIVE .. so don't judge me.<br>
<br>
If you don't know what KRULL is ... well, here it is:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/B000056WR3/qid=1066187992/sr=8-3/ref=sr_8_3/102-6463907-3852964?v=glance&amp;s=dvd&amp;n=507846" target="top">Click Here</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
